            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Evelyn Kuang is a product of San Francisco\u2019s fog-laced avenues and entrepreneurial spirit. Born in the Outer Sunset to parents who emigrated from Hong Kong in the late 1970s, her childhood was filled with the scents of steaming fabric and the constant hum of her mother\u2019s sewing machine. Her parents ran a small but respected tailor shop, instilling in Evelyn an early appreciation for craftsmanship and the language of textiles. While they hoped she would pursue a more stable career, they couldn't deny her innate eye for style.\n\nChoosing to stay local, Evelyn attended San Francisco State University, earning a degree in Fashion Merchandising. She began her career on the bustling sales floor of a Union Square department store, quickly distinguishing herself with her keen understanding of both product and client. She climbed the ladder steadily, moving from department manager to buyer, her ambition a quiet but powerful engine. The key turning point came in her mid-thirties, after a long-term relationship ended. Heartbroken but resolute, she channeled her energy entirely into her career, accepting a high-pressure role as Store Director for a luxury European brand opening a new boutique in Hayes Valley.\n\nNow at 40, Evelyn\u2019s life is a study in curated discipline. Her day starts with a strong coffee in her chic SoMa apartment before she catches the Muni for the short ride to work. As a director, she\u2019s a mentor, a strategist, and a problem-solver, orchestrating the store\u2019s daily performance with practiced ease. Her social circle is small and intimate, comprising a few industry colleagues and a childhood friend who keeps her grounded.\n\nDespite her professional success, a new dream is taking shape. Evelyn feels the pull of her roots, envisioning a small, independent boutique of her own\u2014one that champions emerging AAPI designers. It wouldn't be just a store, but a tribute to her parents' legacy and a platform for new voices. For Evelyn, who has seen her city transform, true success now means building something personal and lasting in the place she has always called home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was eight, standing on a stool in her parents\u2019 Sunset tailor shop. Her father, usually stern behind his spectacles, unrolled a bolt of heavy silk brocade. \u201cFeel,\u201d he\u2019d said in Cantonese, letting her hold the cool, weighted end. It felt like holding a secret, both heavy and alive. He wasn\u2019t just showing her fabric; he was entrusting her with its story. That moment taught her that textiles had a language, a lesson that would become the foundation of her entire career.\n\n***\n\n2.\nIn her early twenties at the Union Square department store, a distressed woman was searching for a mother-of-the-groom dress, hating everything she tried. Evelyn quietly put aside the trendy pieces and brought out a classic, impeccably structured sheath dress in a deep sapphire. The woman\u2019s posture changed instantly in the mirror. Seeing that flicker of renewed confidence ignited a deep, fulfilling warmth in Evelyn. It cemented her belief that her work wasn\u2019t about selling clothes, but about restoring dignity.\n\n***\n\n3.\nThe week after he left, the silence of their SoMa apartment was deafening. While numbly packing his books into a box, her laptop chimed. It was the final offer for the Store Director position, a role she\u2019d thought was a long shot. Looking from the box to the glowing screen, the raw ache of heartbreak gave way to a cold, clear resolve. She would build an empire so magnificent it would leave no room for ghosts. That night, she accepted the job.\n\n***\n\n4.\nIt was the first anniversary party for her Hayes Valley boutique. The store was humming, champagne flutes clinked, and her team moved with the effortless grace she had taught them. Watching from her office doorway, she felt a profound, yet distant, sense of pride. This was the pinnacle she had fought for. But as she saw the city\u2019s elite admiring objects behind glass, she realized she hadn't built a home, but a beautiful museum. The success felt hollow, sparking the first search for something more.\n\n***\n\n5.\nLast fall, visiting her parents, the scent of her mother ironing a silk blouse filled their small apartment. As her mother\u2019s hands expertly smoothed the fabric, Evelyn scrolled through her phone and saw an article about a brilliant, young AAPI designer struggling to find a retailer. The smell of the steam, the sight of her mother\u2019s craft, and the designer's story coalesced. The idea for her own boutique arrived not as a plan, but as a homecoming\u2014a way to finally weave her past and future together."
